    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nNeovim is leaking memory when used with texlab.\n\nThe memory leak happens only in insert mode. As soon as I start typing, RAM usage starts rising (some 50MB per line) and doesn't stop until I restart neovim or I run out of RAM.\n\nEditing other filetypes doesn't cause the issue. Since Neovim is the process leaking memory I thought this was the repo to post.\n\nLSPs are configured in native neovim. Texlab is installed and working. If I disable texlab at lsp.lua and restart neovim, the memory leak stops. Disabling the LSP with :lsp disable on the active buffer doesn't stop the leak immediately, but after typing some more it stops adding RAM usage.\n\nProblem persists after starting neovim with `nvim --clean` and manually configuring the LSP with:\n\n```\n:lua vim.lsp.config[\"texlab\"] = { cmd = { \"texlab\" } }\n:lua vim.lsp.enable(\"texlab\")\n:lua vim.lsp.log.set_level('debug')\n```\n\nAttached are the lsp.log file from neovim, the log file from texlab, and the .tex/.bib files used to reproduce the error.\n\n[lsp.log](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/26648169/lsp.log)\n[texlab.log](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/26648170/texlab.log)\n\n[files.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/26648189/files.zip)\n\nThe .bib file that I'm using has as lot of unused entries in the latex file. Feels like neovim is not garbage collecting the error msgs from the LSP, because if I remove the .bib reference from the latex file, the memory leak is severely reduced.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim --clean\n:lua vim.lsp.config[\"texlab\"] = { cmd = { \"texlab\" } }\n:lua vim.lsp.enable(\"texlab\")\n:lua vim.lsp.log.set_level('debug')\n\nOpen the attached .tex file and start typing in insert mode.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nMemory usage stays constant.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNot sure as vim doesn't have native LSP.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux x86_64\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nfoot 1.26.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nfoot\n\n### Installation\n\npacman",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I checked the log which you provide .. seems 25 keystrokes produced 150 publishDiagnostics, 6 per keystroke. texlab republishes diagnostics for every project file on each change. The .bib notifications all contain the same ~480 \"Unused entry\" diagnostics, but `on_publish_diagnostics` processes the full set every time, converts all diagnostics to lua tables, copies buffer lines, resets extmarks. With debug logging on, the RPC layer also vim.inspect()s each notification before the handler runs. This adds up fast during continuous typing.\n\nDebouncing on_publish_diagnostics in insert mode for large payloads may resolve the issue. Only keep the latest notification per (client, URI) and process it using a short timer . 😮‍💨",
